1. What is Docker?

Docker is a platform used to develop, package, and run applications inside containers.

A container is a lightweight package that contains:

Application code
Libraries
Dependencies
Runtime environment

This helps the application run the same way on:

Your laptop
Testing server
Production server
Why Docker is used
Eliminates “works on my machine” problem
Easy deployment
Faster than virtual machines
Portable and scalable
Useful in DevOps and CI/CD pipelines
2. Docker Architecture

Docker follows a Client-Server architecture.

Main Components
1. Docker Client

The command line where users type commands like:

docker build
docker run
docker ps
2. Docker Daemon (dockerd)

Background service that:

Builds containers
Runs containers
Manages images and networks
3. Docker Images

Read-only templates used to create containers.

Example:

ubuntu
nginx
node
mysql
4. Docker Containers

Running instances of Docker images.

Example:

docker run nginx
5. Docker Registry

Stores Docker images.

Main registry:
Docker Hub

Docker Architecture Flow
User
  ↓
Docker Client
  ↓
Docker Daemon
  ↓
Images → Containers
  ↓
Docker Registry (Docker Hub)
3. What is Jenkins?

Jenkins is an open-source CI/CD automation tool.

CI/CD means:

CI → Continuous Integration
CD → Continuous Delivery/Deployment

Jenkins automates:

Build
Testing
Deployment
Why Jenkins is used

Instead of manually:

Writing code
Compiling
Testing
Deploying

Jenkins does it automatically whenever code changes.

Jenkins Workflow
Developer pushes code to GitHub
        ↓
Jenkins detects change
        ↓
Build project
        ↓
Run tests
        ↓
Deploy application
4. What is JDK?

Java Development Kit (JDK) is a package required to develop and run Java applications.

It contains:

JRE (Java Runtime Environment)
Java Compiler (javac)
Java libraries
Development tools
Difference Between JDK, JRE, JVM
Component	Purpose
JVM	Runs Java bytecode
JRE	Provides environment to run Java apps
JDK	Used to develop Java applications
5. How to Install JDK on Windows
Step 1: Download JDK

Go to:

Oracle JDK Downloads

OR

OpenJDK (Temurin) Downloads

Step 2: Install
Download Windows .exe
Double click installer
Click Next → Install

Example path:

C:\Program Files\Java\jdk-21
Step 3: Set Environment Variables
Open:
This PC → Properties → Advanced System Settings → Environment Variables
Create JAVA_HOME

Under System Variables:

Variable Name:
JAVA_HOME
Variable Value:
C:\Program Files\Java\jdk-21
Edit PATH

Add:

%JAVA_HOME%\bin
Step 4: Verify Installation

Open CMD:

java -version
javac -version

If installed correctly:

java version "21"
6. How to Install Docker on Windows
Requirements
Windows 10/11
Virtualization enabled in BIOS
WSL2 support
Step 1: Download Docker Desktop

Go to:

Docker Desktop for Windows

Step 2: Install Docker Desktop
Run installer
Enable:
WSL2
Hyper-V (if asked)

Restart system after installation.

Step 3: Start Docker

Open Docker Desktop.

Wait until:

Docker Engine running
Step 4: Verify Installation

Open CMD:

docker --version

Check Docker working:

docker run hello-world

If successful:

Hello from Docker!
7. How to Install Jenkins on Windows
Prerequisite

JDK must already be installed.

Step 1: Download Jenkins

Go to:

Jenkins Official Website

Download:

Windows installer (.msi)
Step 2: Install Jenkins
Run .msi
Choose installation path
Jenkins installs as Windows service
Step 3: Start Jenkins

Open browser:

http://localhost:8080
Step 4: Unlock Jenkins

Password file location:

C:\Program Files\Jenkins\secrets\initialAdminPassword

Copy password into browser.

Step 5: Install Suggested Plugins

Click:

Install Suggested Plugins
Step 6: Create Admin User

Set:

Username
Password
Email
8. Basic DevOps Flow Using All
Java Code
   ↓
Build using Maven
   ↓
Jenkins automates build
   ↓
Docker creates container
   ↓
Application deployed
Important Commands
Docker Commands
docker images
docker ps
docker ps -a
docker run nginx
docker stop <container_id>
docker rm <container_id>
Jenkins Service Commands (Windows)
net start jenkins
net stop jenkins
